{
  "What does marine science primarily study?": "",
  "Oceans and other saltwater environments": "",
  "Only freshwater rivers": "",
  "Only weather patterns over land": "",
  "Only mountain ecosystems": "",
  "Marine science focuses on oceans, seas, coasts, estuaries, and the organisms and processes found there. It is not limited to rivers, land weather, or mountain systems.": "",
  "Which environment would a marine scientist MOST likely study?": "",
  "A grassland prairie": "",
  "An alpine glacier only": "",
  "A desert dune": "",
  "A coral reef": "",
  "Coral reefs are marine ecosystems found in saltwater. Deserts, prairies, and alpine land environments are studied by other branches of Earth and life science.": "",
  "About how much of Earth's surface is covered by the ocean?": "",
  "About 50%": "",
  "About 25%": "",
  "About 10%": "",
  "About 70%": "",
  "The global ocean covers roughly 71% of Earth's surface, which is one reason marine science is so important to understanding the planet.": "",
  "Marine science is considered interdisciplinary because it combines:": "",
  "Only mathematics and art": "",
  "Only astronomy and geology": "",
  "Only biology": "",
  "Biology, chemistry, geology, and physics": "",
  "Marine science draws from several sciences at once. Scientists study marine organisms, water chemistry, seafloor geology, and physical processes like waves and currents.": "",
  "An estuary forms where:": "",
  "Freshwater from rivers mixes with ocean water": "",
  "A forest becomes a grassland": "",
  "A volcano erupts under ice": "",
  "Two deserts meet": "",
  "Estuaries are coastal areas where river freshwater mixes with saltwater from the sea, creating a brackish and highly productive habitat.": "",
  "Which group includes tiny organisms that drift with ocean currents?": "",
  "Plankton": "",
  "Predators": "",
  "Benthos": "",
  "Nekton": "",
  "Plankton drift with water movement rather than swimming strongly against it. They include both plant-like phytoplankton and animal-like zooplankton.": "",
  "Animals such as whales, tuna, and sharks are examples of:": "",
  "Decomposers only": "",
  "Nekton are active swimmers that can move independently of currents. Whales, tuna, squid, and sharks are common examples.": "",
  "Organisms that live on or near the seafloor are called:": "",
  "Atmospherics": "",
  "Benthos live on, in, or near the ocean bottom. Crabs, sea stars, clams, and many worms are benthic organisms.": "",
  "The photic zone is the part of the ocean that:": "",
  "Receives enough sunlight for photosynthesis": "",
  "Contains no living things": "",
  "Exists only in freshwater lakes": "",
  "Is completely frozen year-round": "",
  "The photic zone is the sunlit upper layer of the ocean. Because light reaches it, photosynthetic organisms such as phytoplankton can live there.": "",
  "Why is marine science important to humans?": "",
  "It only helps people who work on ships": "",
  "It only studies extinct species": "",
  "It is unrelated to weather and climate": "",
  "It helps us understand climate, food resources, and ocean ecosystems": "",
  "Marine science matters because oceans influence weather, climate, oxygen production, food webs, transportation, and biodiversity.": "",
  "What is oceanography?": "",
  "The study of only fish anatomy": "",
  "The study of stars and galaxies": "",
  "The scientific study of the ocean and its processes": "",
  "The study of mountain building": "",
  "Oceanography is a major branch of marine science that examines seawater, currents, waves, seafloor features, and marine life.": "",
  "What is a marine ecosystem?": "",
  "A single species living alone": "",
  "Only the chemistry of seawater": "",
  "A type of submarine vehicle": "",
  "A community of organisms interacting with each other and with ocean conditions": "",
  "An ecosystem includes living things and the nonliving environment around them. In marine ecosystems, that includes water, light, temperature, nutrients, and habitat.": "",
  "What is an estuary?": "",
  "A floating patch of sea ice": "",
  "A deep trench in the open ocean": "",
  "A coastal area where freshwater and saltwater mix": "",
  "A storm system over water": "",
  "Estuaries are transition zones between river systems and the ocean. Because nutrients are plentiful there, they are among the most productive habitats on Earth.": "",
  "What does the term 'plankton' mean in marine science?": "",
  "Rocks found on beaches": "",
  "Animals that live only on coral reefs": "",
  "Organisms that drift with currents": "",
  "Large animals that hunt in groups": "",
  "Plankton are not defined by size alone but by their inability to swim strongly against currents. They are a foundation of many marine food webs.": "",
  "What does the term 'nekton' refer to?": "",
  "Organisms rooted to the seafloor": "",
  "Actively swimming organisms that can move against currents": "",
  "The salt content of seawater": "",
  "Microscopic bacteria only": "",
  "Nekton includes strong swimmers such as fish, marine mammals, and squid. Their movement is not controlled mainly by drifting currents.": "",
  "What does the term 'benthos' refer to?": "",
  "Organisms that live only in the open atmosphere": "",
  "Organisms that live on or near the seafloor": "",
  "Ocean currents near the surface": "",
  "Floating sea ice": "",
  "Benthos may crawl on the bottom, burrow into sediment, or attach to rocks. Sea stars, clams, corals, and many worms are benthic organisms.": "",
  "What is the intertidal zone?": "",
  "The coastal area between high tide and low tide": "",
  "The deepest part of the ocean trench": "",
  "A part of the ocean with no waves": "",
  "The warmest layer of Earth's atmosphere": "",
  "The intertidal zone is covered with water at high tide and exposed at low tide. Organisms there must survive changing moisture, temperature, and wave conditions.": "",
  "What is salinity?": "",
  "The amount of dissolved salts in water": "",
  "The depth of the seafloor": "",
  "The temperature of ocean water": "",
  "The speed of a wave": "",
  "Salinity measures how much dissolved salt is present in water. It affects water density, circulation, and which organisms can survive in a habitat.": "",
  "What does biodiversity mean?": "",
  "The age of ocean water": "",
  "The variety of living organisms in an area": "",
  "The number of beaches in a region": "",
  "The speed of ocean currents": "",
  "Biodiversity describes the variety of life at different levels, including species, genes, and ecosystems. High biodiversity often supports ecosystem stability.": "",
  "What is marine conservation?": "",
  "Collecting every organism from a reef": "",
  "Studying only fossils from the ocean": "",
  "Protecting ocean ecosystems and using marine resources responsibly": "",
  "Building more roads near beaches": "",
  "Marine conservation aims to protect habitats, preserve biodiversity, and manage fisheries and coastal resources so ecosystems remain healthy over time.": "",
  "A coastal bay suddenly develops a large harmful algal bloom after weeks of fertilizer runoff from nearby farms. Which factor most likely contributed to the bloom?": "",
  "The bay turning into freshwater ice": "",
  "A complete loss of plankton": "",
  "A decrease in sunlight to zero": "",
  "Extra nutrients entering the water": "",
  "Fertilizer runoff adds nitrogen and phosphorus to coastal water. Those nutrients can fuel rapid algae growth, producing a harmful algal bloom.": "",
  "After an oil spill, many seabirds are found coated in oil and unable to stay warm. Why is the oil especially dangerous for them?": "",
  "It damages the waterproofing and insulation of their feathers": "",
  "It causes the tides to stop": "",
  "It makes birds able to breathe underwater": "",
  "It instantly turns ocean water into freshwater": "",
  "Bird feathers normally trap air and repel water. Oil breaks down that protection, causing birds to lose heat quickly and making it harder for them to float and fly.": "",
  "A coral reef turns pale after a long period of unusually warm water. Which explanation best fits this observation?": "",
  "The reef has moved into the deep aphotic zone": "",
  "The salinity has dropped to zero permanently": "",
  "The corals are bleaching because heat stress caused them to lose symbiotic algae": "",
  "The corals have changed into plankton": "",
  "Coral bleaching happens when stressed corals expel the algae that normally live inside them. Without those algae, the coral looks white and may die if stress continues.": "",
  "A fish population in a coastal estuary drops after nearby mangroves are removed. Which is the best explanation?": "",
  "The Moon no longer affected the tides": "",
  "All plankton became benthos immediately": "",
  "The estuary stopped mixing fresh and salt water": "",
  "Young fish lost an important nursery habitat": "",
  "Mangroves protect shorelines and provide shelter and feeding areas for juvenile fish. Removing them can reduce survival of young fish and harm nearby fisheries.": "",
  "A student lowers a light sensor from the ocean surface and notices that sunlight decreases rapidly with depth until photosynthesis is no longer possible. The sensor has most likely left the:": "",
  "Beach dune": "",
  "Photic zone": "",
  "Intertidal zone": "",
  "Estuary": "",
  "The photic zone is the sunlit layer where enough light exists for photosynthesis. Below it, light becomes too weak for most photosynthetic organisms.": "",
  "After several days of heavy rain, a scientist measures lower salinity in an estuary. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "The estuary became part of the deep ocean": "",
  "Extra freshwater diluted the saltwater": "",
  "Salt was removed by sharks": "",
  "Tides permanently stopped moving": "",
  "Salinity is the amount of dissolved salt in water. When more river water enters an estuary, it lowers salinity by diluting the seawater already there.": "",
  "A whale swims across an ocean current instead of simply drifting with it. In marine science, the whale would be classified as:": "",
  "Sediment": "",
  "Nekton are capable of active swimming and directional movement. A whale is not drifting passively like plankton and does not live on the bottom like benthos.": "",
  "At low tide, a student sees barnacles and sea stars exposed to air on coastal rocks. Which habitat is the student observing?": "",
  "The open-ocean photic zone only": "",
  "The intertidal zone": "",
  "A freshwater wetland": "",
  "The abyssal plain": "",
  "The intertidal zone lies between high and low tide lines. Organisms there must tolerate being underwater part of the day and exposed to air at other times.": "",
  "A sea turtle eats a floating plastic bag because it resembles a jellyfish. Which marine science issue does this scenario best illustrate?": "",
  "Natural plate tectonics": "",
  "The formation of estuaries": "",
  "Marine pollution harming wildlife": "",
  "A decrease in biodiversity due to mountains": "",
  "Plastic pollution is a major conservation issue. Marine animals can mistake debris for food, leading to injury, starvation, or death.": "",
  "A coastal town wants to manage its fisheries without causing long-term population collapse. Which marine science approach would be most responsible?": "",
  "Catch as many fish as possible every season": "",
  "Use catch limits based on population data and habitat health": "",
  "Ignore breeding seasons and nursery habitats": "",
  "Remove predators from the ecosystem first": "",
  "Sustainable fisheries management depends on scientific data, including population size, reproduction, and habitat condition. Marine science supports harvesting resources without destroying ecosystems.": ""
}